Peter Caine began making art while recovering from an injury at the US Naval Hospital in Jacksonville, FL. Not long after enrolling at the Kansas Art Institute, he moved to New York City. His work has been included in exhibitions such as Greater New York 2005 at MoMA PS1 (Caine‚Äôs installation ‚ÄúOverseer‚Äù was a highlight of the show), or Silicone Valley (MoMA PS1, 2007); he showed at Jack the Pelican Presents, Derek Eller Gallery, ATM Gallery and Exit Art. Reviews have appeared in The New York Times, The Brooklyn Rail, The New York Post, Art News or Art Forum

He‚Äôs also quite artistic. In several videos on his Youtube channel he presents morbid animatronics and sculpted figures. In a 2016 video he revealed a 1998 Ronald Reagan-inspired piece called ‚ÄúRonny Did a Boom Boom‚Äù, no doubt channeling the unforgettably creepy 1986 Genesis music video for ‚ÄúLand of Confusion.‚Äù He even has an installation display of an animatronic Donald Trump dry-humping watermelon and sheep, currently featured in a Manhattan gallery.
